1645, September 3.

1Jllaister Mason—This Company are agreed (nullo contmdicente>‚2 10 that Captin Mason shall bee sworne burgos, freely, payinge nothinge for the same (it to bee noe preiudice nor example for the future, to any other), for theis reasons : Because

1. He is Captin of many Townsemen‚ volunteers sor defence of the Towne, and hath performed yat place faithfully, with great 15 paines and charg.

2. Hee is of the Committee‚ and therein hath [done] and may doe the Towne good service.

3. Hee is of noe trade or occupacion, manuall or other, that will hinder or preludice any former burges in any respect, neither will hee 20 (if any occation bee), hinder‚ but doe what hee can for, the good of the Corporacion and the members of it.

Captin Mason was this day sent for and sworne burges (accordinge to the former vote this day), before this Companye.
